Phase 1, Lesson 5: Functions
This is the biggest concept in programming. Everything else builds on it.
The Analogy — A Recipe Card
A recipe isn't food. It's instructions for making food. You write it once, then you can make that dish a hundred times without rewriting the recipe.
A function is a recipe for code. You write the instructions once, give it a name, and call it whenever you need it.
javascript// Writing the recipe
function greetClient(name) {
  console.log(`Welcome to Fades & Facials, ${name}!`)
}

// Using the recipe
greetClient("Britton")
greetClient("Marcus")
greetClient("DeShawn")
name is called a parameter — a blank in the recipe that gets filled in each time you call it.
Functions That Give You Something Back
javascriptfunction calculateTotal(price, tip) {
  return price + tip
}

const total = calculateTotal(45, 9)
console.log(total)  // 54
The return keyword hands a value back out of the function. Without return, the function does work but gives nothing back — like a machine that processes but never outputs.
Three Ways to Write the Same Function
You'll see all three in real codebases. They all do the same thing:
javascript// 1. Function declaration — hoisted, can be called before it's defined
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b
}

// 2. Function expression — stored in a variable
const add = function(a, b) {
  return a + b
}

// 3. Arrow function — the modern way, what you'll use most
const add = (a, b) => a + b
That last one — the arrow function — if it fits on one line, you can skip the return keyword and the curly braces. The result is returned automatically.

