--typescript — TypeScript isn't a plugin, it's a superset of JavaScript that adds static type checking. It compiles down to plain JS. Think of it as JavaScript with a strict spellchecker that catches type mismatches before your code ever runs. You'll write .tsx files instead of .jsx.
--app — tells create-next-app to use the App Router (app/ folder) instead of the old Pages Router. Nothing to do with React itself — it's a Next.js routing architecture choice. You just spent 10 minutes learning this structure.
--no-src-dir — by default some setups wrap everything in a src/ folder so your structure is src/app/, src/components/. This flag skips that wrapper and puts app/ at the root. Flatter structure, easier imports, more common in production Next.js repos.
--import-alias "@/*" — instead of writing ../../../components/Button to import something, you write @/components/Button from anywhere in the project. The @ maps to your project root. You'll use this constantly.

