Your Question — The Best One Yet

"You can have a constant true or false? Why is the yes/no in a let but const has true/false?"

My example was sloppy and I'm glad you caught it. The type of box — let or const — has nothing to do with what you put inside it. You can put a boolean in either one. Here's the real distinction:
javascript// const means this box is SEALED — value never changes
const isLoggedIn = false      // once logged out, stays logged out in this variable
const GRAVITY = 9.8           // physics doesn't change

// let means this box can be UPDATED
let isOpen = true             // shop opens and closes throughout the day
isOpen = false                // closing time — valid, because it's let
So the question to ask yourself when writing any variable is: will this value ever need to change during the program's life?
If yes → let. If no → const.
A user's login status might change. Whether your app is running on Earth probably won't.

