Phase 1, Lesson 4: Conditionals
Every program makes decisions. The barbershop site will need to make dozens: Is the shop open right now? Is the client logged in? Does this service cost over $50?
The Analogy — A Bouncer
A bouncer at a club has one job: check a condition, make a decision.
javascriptconst clientAge = 17
const minimumAge = 18

if (clientAge >= minimumAge) {
  console.log("Welcome in")
} else {
  console.log("Not tonight")
}
The >= means "greater than or equal to." JavaScript evaluates the condition — is 17 >= 18? No. So it skips the first block and runs the else.
The Comparison Operators
javascript5 > 3    // greater than         → true
5 < 3    // less than            → false
5 >= 5   // greater or equal     → true
5 <= 4   // less or equal        → false
5 === 5  // strictly equal       → true
5 !== 3  // not equal            → true
Note the triple equals ===. JavaScript also has == but seniors never use it. Here's why:
javascript5 == "5"   // true  ← JavaScript tries to be "helpful" and converts types
5 === "5"  // false ← strict check: number 5 is NOT the same as string "5"
Always ===. The == causes bugs that take hours to find.

