Phase 1, Lesson 6: Arrays & Loops
The barbershop site has a services list. That list is an array. Every service on the page comes from looping over that array and rendering each one. This is the foundation of how every website's content works.
The Analogy — A Numbered Shelf
An array is a shelf with numbered slots starting at 0. You put items on the shelf, and you grab them by their slot number.
javascriptconst services = ["Fade", "Beard Trim", "Facial", "Shave"]

console.log(services[0])  // "Fade"
console.log(services[2])  // "Facial"
console.log(services.length)  // 4
That [0] is called the index. The first item is always index 0, not 1. This trips everyone up the first time.
The for Loop — Do This For Every Item
javascriptconst services = ["Fade", "Beard Trim", "Facial", "Shave"]

for (let i = 0; i < services.length; i++) {
  console.log(`Service ${i + 1}: ${services[i]}`)
}
Breaking down for (let i = 0; i < services.length; i++):

let i = 0 — start at index 0
i < services.length — keep going while i is less than 4
i++ — after each loop, add 1 to i

The Modern Way — forEach
The for loop above works but looks noisy. Here's how seniors actually write it:
javascriptservices.forEach((service) => {
  console.log(service)
})
Same result, half the code. forEach hands each item to your arrow function one at a time. The parameter name service is just a label you pick — it could be anything, but name it something that makes sense.

