The actual answer to my question: you add "use client" as the very first line of the file. That's the directive that tells Next.js to ship this component's JavaScript to the browser so it can use useState, event listeners, and anything that requires interactivity.
Why not make everything client components: Server Components render on the server and ship zero JavaScript to the browser. That's faster page loads and better SEO — the HTML arrives fully formed. Client components ship a JavaScript bundle the browser has to download, parse, and execute before anything interactive works. You want as few client components as possible, as far down the component tree as possible.
Rule of thumb: if it doesn't need clicks, state, or browser APIs — keep it a Server Component.

