The Three iOS Bugs — Root Cause Diagnosis
Bug 1 — Scroll listener doesn't fire on iOS Safari
iOS Safari doesn't fire scroll events on window the same way desktop browsers do. It batches scroll events and delivers them after the momentum scroll completes, not during. The fix is two-part: add { passive: true } to the event listener (tells iOS it can scroll without waiting for your JS), and also listen on document as a fallback.
Bug 2 — Hamburger button too small and doesn't respond to taps
Two separate problems. Size: no minimum touch target — Apple HIG requires 44×44px minimum. iOS drops tap events on anything smaller. Interactivity: the button has no type="button" and no touch-manipulation CSS — iOS Safari has a 300ms synthetic click delay on elements that don't explicitly opt out.
Bug 3 — backdrop-blur-sm silently breaks on iOS under GPU memory pressure
This is the most dangerous one because it fails invisibly. When iOS Safari runs low on GPU memory (common on older iPhones), it silently aborts the backdrop-filter render pass, making the element completely transparent or invisible. The navbar disappears with zero error. The fix: remove backdrop-blur-sm entirely and use a solid or high-opacity color instead.

