Phase 1, Lesson 7: Array Iterators
You know forEach now. But there are three more that you'll use constantly in the barbershop site — probably every single day you write React.
The difference between them in one sentence each:

forEach — loop and do something, gives nothing back
map — loop and transform every item, gives you a new array
filter — loop and keep only items that pass a test, gives you a smaller array

map — Transform Every Item
javascriptconst prices = [35, 20, 65, 45, 25]

const withTax = prices.map((price) => price * 1.08)
console.log(withTax)
// [37.8, 21.6, 70.2, 48.6, 27]
The original prices array is untouched. map always returns a brand new array.
filter — Keep Only What Passes
javascriptconst prices = [35, 20, 65, 45, 25]

const premiumOnly = prices.filter((price) => price >= 40)
console.log(premiumOnly)
// [65, 45]
Chaining Them Together
This is where it gets powerful. In React, this pattern renders your entire services list to the screen:
javascriptconst services = [
  { name: "Fade", price: 35 },
  { name: "Facial", price: 65 },
  { name: "Beard Trim", price: 20 },
  { name: "Hot Shave", price: 45 }
]

// Get only services over $30, then format them for display
const featured = services
  .filter((service) => service.price > 30)
  .map((service) => `${service.name} — $${service.price}`)

console.log(featured)
// ["Fade — $35", "Facial — $65", "Hot Shave — $45"]
Notice something new there — { name: "Fade", price: 35 }. That's an object inside an array. Each service has multiple properties. This is exactly how your barbershop services data will actually be structured.

