One sentence answer. The concept is: Server Components can run server-side code directly — async/await, database calls, file reads — without needing an intermediary API route. API routes exist for client components that need to fetch data after page load, or for external services that need an endpoint to hit.
Which fits a public services page that doesn't change often? 👇You said: p9 is go through an api routep9 is go through an api route
whats next8:04 PMClaude responded: Close — but actually the opposite is correct for this case.Close — but actually the opposite is correct for this case.
A Server Component runs on the server at request time. It can call the database directly, the same way an API route would — but without the extra network hop. There's no browser involved, so there's no reason to create a middleman API route.
typescript// app/services/page.tsx — Server Component
// This function runs on the server, never in the browser
async function getServices() {
  const { data } = await supabase.from('services').select('*')
  return data
}

export default async function ServicesPage() {
  const services = await getServices()  // direct DB call, no API needed
  return ( /* render services */ )
}
API routes are for when a client component needs to fetch data after the page loads — like a search filter, a form submission, or anything that happens because of user interaction. The admin dashboard will use API routes because the barber's actions (saving edits, uploading photos) happen client-side after login.
Rule of thumb: public read-only data = Server Component direct fetch. User-triggered mutations = API route.

