Phase 1, Lesson 8: Objects
You've already seen objects without me formally introducing them. Remember this from the last lesson:
javascript{ name: "Fade", price: 35 }
That's an object. Now let's understand what they actually are.
The Analogy — A Business Card
An array is a numbered list. An object is a business card — it groups related information about one thing under named labels.
javascriptconst barber = {
  name: "Marcus",
  specialty: "Fades",
  yearsExperience: 8,
  isAvailable: true
}
Each label is called a key. Each piece of data is a value. Together they're called key-value pairs.
Accessing the Data
javascriptconsole.log(barber.name)           // "Marcus"
console.log(barber.yearsExperience) // 8

// Bracket notation — useful when the key is dynamic
console.log(barber["specialty"])   // "Fades"
Objects Inside Arrays — The Real World Pattern
This is how your barbershop services will actually live in code:
javascriptconst services = [
  { id: 1, name: "Fade", price: 35, duration: 30 },
  { id: 2, name: "Facial", price: 65, duration: 60 },
  { id: 3, name: "Beard Trim", price: 20, duration: 15 }
]

// Get the name of the second service
console.log(services[1].name)  // "Facial"

// Loop over all services and display them
services.forEach((service) => {
  console.log(`${service.name} — $${service.price} (${service.duration} mins)`)
})
Destructuring — The Senior Shortcut
Instead of writing service.name, service.price everywhere, you can unpack the values you need in one line:
javascriptconst { name, price } = services[0]
console.log(name)   // "Fade"
console.log(price)  // 35
This is called destructuring. You'll see it constantly in React components. It's not magic — it's just shorthand for:
javascriptconst name = services[0].name
const price = services[0].price

