The scroll listener fires (desktop proves it), state updates happen, but iOS isn't re-rendering the fixed element. This is a known iOS compositing bug.
Fix `components/Navbar.tsx` — iOS compositing prevents fixed element repaints.

ROOT CAUSE CONFIRMED: iOS Safari does not reliably repaint fixed-position elements 
when only className changes. The scroll listener fires and state updates correctly,
but the visual repaint is silently skipped due to GPU compositing layer caching.

REQUIRED CHANGES:

1. Change the nav element from a className-only approach to also use inline style
   for the transform, forcing a compositing layer update on every scroll:

Replace the nav opening tag with exactly this:

<nav
  style={{
    transform: 'translateZ(0)',
    WebkitTransform: 'translateZ(0)',
  }}
  className={`fixed top-0 left-0 right-0 z-50 px-6 text-white transition-all duration-300 ${
    scrolled
      ? 'mt-4 mx-4 md:mx-8 rounded-2xl bg-white/40 py-3 shadow-lg'
      : 'pt-4 mx-0 bg-transparent pb-4 border-b border-white/25'
  }`}
>

2. The `translateZ(0)` inline style is permanent and static — it forces iOS to 
   promote the nav to its own GPU compositing layer on initial paint, so className 
   changes trigger a repaint instead of being ignored.

3. `WebkitTransform` is the iOS Safari vendor-prefixed version — both are required.

4. Keep the scrolled/non-scrolled class logic exactly as shown above.

5. Keep all existing scroll listeners, debug overlay, and hamburger fixes unchanged.

